at Sam Binkley demonstrates is aligned closely with economic neoliberalism. Happiness as Enterprise blends theoretical argumentation and empirical description in an engaging and accessible analysis that brings governmentality theory into contact with sociological theories of practice and temporality, particularly in the work of Pierre Bourdieu. This book invites readers not only to consider the new discourse on happiness for its relation to contemporary formations of power, but to rethink many of the assumptions of governmentality theory in a manner sensitive to the mundane practices and everyday agencies of government, and the unique and specific temporalities these practices imply.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aHappiness. 0aNeoliberalism. 0aPower (Social sciences). 0aSelf-culture. 0aState, The. 4aCultural Studies : Cultural Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Critical Theory. 4aPolitics and Law : Political Philosophy. 4aPsychology : Psychology. 4aSociology : Sociology. 7aSELF-HELP / Personal Growth / Happiness.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143844985240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438449852423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438449852/original  a978-3-11-149015-1  SUNY Press eBook Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles